I have a 24&quot; white Intel iMac that I use for audio recording
and editing.

I've partitioned the internal hard drive into several
partitions, including a large &quot;boot partition&quot; and 3 small
(8gig) &quot;project&quot; partitions.

This way, I keep all my audio production files &quot;together&quot; in
a single partition, which I can then optimize without
affecting _other_ partitions.

One of the standard recommendations I've seen re audio (and
video) production is, &quot;don't use the same drive for both
your system/apps and your sound files&quot;.

The &quot;project partition&quot; concept works fine for me. In fact
it seems to work _better than_ using two drives on my older
g4. I record using a Presonus Firebox (firewire) interface
and have had virtually no input problems (cracks, pops,
etc.) since moving over to the iMac.

But then again, I also believe in defragmenting/disk
optimization, as well. Guess I'm in the minority in that
respect. But that, too, works for me. Others' mileage may
vary... :)

- John
(I also created a &quot;backup boot&quot; partition with a separate
copy of the OS)
