Let's be generous: it was useful up to Mac OS 8.0, if you had a large
hard drive and wanted to avoid wasting too much space due to lots of
small files and HFS block sizes getting too big. With 8.1 and HFS+ that
reason went away.

It might also be useful in the Mac OS X era if you want multiple
bootable Mac OS X systems. Apart from that, I haven't bothered for my
main drives.

I partition my backup drives for the same reason - multiple bootable
clones, possibly based on different versions of Mac OS X. It is also a
handy way to limit Time Machine's growth on a backup drive.

