&gt; separate back-up of each.  I can also see circumstances where I might set
&gt; &quot;no-atime&quot; on specific partitions to speed things up, but this discussion
&gt; here has led me to question why partitioning is recommended and part of
&gt; the default installation for many Unices.

&gt; Is it just an out of date tradition?
">

I help administer some linux systems at work. Partitioning for Unix
systems has been done for facilitating backups and to help manage the
various file systems involved in a typical Unix configuration.

Backups are usually done by partition. If you put stuff that doesn't
change (software applications and libraries) in one partition, and
stuff that does change (user files) in another partition, you can do
frequent backups on the rapidly-changing stuff and less frequent
backups on the more static stuff. If it is all in one, big partition,
the backup software will have to do a scan on the entire disk drive to
find out what has changed.

Another reason is to manage partition mounts. In a typical Unix system
environment NFS mounts are used to share common software and user files
among several machines. Having various types of file systems in their
own partitions affords flexibility in selecting what files are
available on any given machine.

Our Unix systems typically have partitions for 1) booting the machine,
2) local system files, 3) local user accounts, 4) shared software, and
5) shared user directories, 6) shared project data, and 7) temporary
working space (that doesn't get backed up).

