It is referring to various SMART parameters, each of which is a counter
which records unusual events of a particular type that the drive has
noticed.

They are comparing the average failure rate of drives which have not
counted any events in a particular SMART parameter (zero count) with
those which have had at least one event counted in the same SMART
parameter (non-zero count).

In other words, they are looking at how many drives failed which had no
recorded errors of a particular type, compared to drives which had
recorded the same error.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; &quot;We find that the group of drives with scan errors are ten times more
&gt; likely to fail than the group with no errors.&quot;
&gt; What is a good way of scanning for hard drive errors on a Mac?  Does
&gt; Disk Utility see errors when it verifies or repairs a partition or drive?
">

Again, this is referring to a particular SMART parameter (scan errors).
The drive scans itself in the background automatically and records any
errors it finds. (See section 3.5.1.) You don't need to do anything to
activate this mechanism - the drive will do it automatically.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; &quot;Previous studies have indicated that temperature deltas as low as
&gt; 15C can nearly double disk drive failure rates&quot;
&gt; What is a temperature delta? Is that a temperature range?
">

Delta means difference. This is saying that at some point on the
temperature scale they observed a doubled rate of drive failures for a
temperature change of 15C.

Looking at figure 4, it shows a failure rate of 7% +/- 0.5% at 20C, and
2% at 35C. Seems more like triple the number of errors to me.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; In Figure 4 its mentions Probability Density.  What is that?
">

This is referring to the histogram on the graph. It shows the
distribution of samples at various temperatures. If you add the height
of all the bars, using the scale on the left margin, you will get 1.00.

The probability density is the proportion of the total samples which
were at that temperature. Note that the error (vertical lines on each
sample of average failure rate) increase as the number of samples drops:
they get more accurate figures for average failure rate if there are a
greater number of samples at a particular temperature.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; In Figure 5 it shows average drive temperatures of
&gt; (15,30)
&gt; (30,35)
">

Not quite. Look closely: it is &quot;[15, 30)&quot; for example.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; up to 45
&gt; Do they mean 15-30?
">

Yes. This is a standard mathematical notation for a range. Square
brackets and parentheses represent a closed or open end of the range. A
square bracket means the range includes that value, a parenthesis means
the range includes everything less (or greater than) that value. Thus
&quot;[15, 30)&quot; means &quot;greater than or equal to 15 and less than 30&quot;.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; If so, that is the temperature range, not the average temperature isn't
&gt; it?  Or perhaps they are saying when a hard drive ranges between an
&gt; average temperature of 15-30.... I always thought an average is a single
&gt; figure and a range has 2 figures.
">

The various shades of grey represent all drives which had an average
temperature within the specified range. For example, the black bars are
all drives with an average temparature between 15C (inclusive) and 30C
(exclusive). It is then measuring average failure rates of drives at
various ages, noting in particular that older drives are more likely to
fail at higher temperatures, while newer drives are more likely to fail
at lower temperatures.

